Juan Diego Latorre Ramirez
on Aug 13, 2023

Hi Arjan! Curiously last night I asked a question related to this topic: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/76887758/how-should-i-structure-modules-in-a-large-python-application.
When I create an API I use this concept of "operations layer" although I have to further structure the project as I show in the question because they are usually large projects. I would like to know your opinion on the subject, in FastAPI applications you consider it more appropriate to "slice" by technical functionality (models, schemas, routes, etc.), in fact it is proposed in the official documentation: https://fastapi.tiangolo .com/tutorial/bigger-applications/. Or do you think it's more appropriate to "slice" by subject area/domain (events, tickets etc), which is usually the approach proposed in Django.

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Aug 30, 2023

Hi Juan, if you're using FastAPI, I'd suggest to follow their recommendation of structuring the project according to technical functionality. This is quite close to what I mention in another lesson of the course about project organization: you typically see things organized according to the particular architecture that you use. So for a backend application, you'd have routes, schema, operations, etc. Within that, you can then further organize things according to subject area (i.e. a specific folder for authentication routes, etc).
